SC writeup

MEET THE EXECUTIVE BOARD

President of UNSC : Siddhanth Chawla

Deputy Presidents of UNSC : Aarav Naik and Yidam Verma

“The United Nations was born from war. Today we must be here for peace.”

•⁠  ⁠António Guterres

Dear Delegates and MUN Directors,

The United Nations Security Council is the pillar which upholds international peace, equipped
with the mandate to take on the threats that traverse borders and endanger the future of humanity. In
today’s day and age, where ongoing conflicts which seem to last far longer than they should slowly pick
away at our food chains and energy markets while undermining international law, once deemed as
unbreakable - the Security Council is one of our last lines of defense.

Our first agenda: “Aftereffects of the lasting Impact of Prolonged Warfare in Ukraine on Global
Food Security, Energy Stability, and the present and future Credibility of International Security
Guarantees”, deals with the continued consequences of the Russia-Ukraine war, a conflict entering its
fourth year. Ukraine, once known as the “breadbasket of Europe”, is now in turmoil, and its fields which
once fed over 400 million people (UN World Food Programme, 2025), are now nothing but ash. As a
result, global wheat exports have significantly fallen, thereby fuelling food insecurity in regions where
bread is a staple. Moreover, sabotaged gas pipelines throughout Europe and economic sanctions on the
Russian economy mean that energy stability is no more than a myth, with inflating prices worldwide.
Furthermore, the deeper we delve into these conflicts we see that the majority of problems stem from the
fragility of international agreements such as the Minsk Agreements, security guarantees which were
violated (European Council on Foreign Relations, 2024) without any concern of international
consequences likely to follow, and the challenges posed toward NATO’s deterrence.

Our second agenda: “Addressing the Humanitarian Crisis and Threats to International Peace and
Security Resulting from the Yemen Conflict through the Formation of an Independent Task Force
Monitored by the UN”, demands action on a tragedy which has lasted for over a decade now. This conflict
has been responsible for 377,00 deaths (Friends Committee on National Legislation, 2023) and 4.5
million Yemeni people (around 14% of the population) displaced from their homes (UNHCR, 2025). The
Red Sea crisis which began in late 2023 threatens the 12% of global trade which passes through the Suez
Canal (consequently having to pass through the Red Sea) (New Zealand Ministry of Foreign Affairs and
Trade, 2021), hence creating a rise in food and fuel costs worldwide. In addition to this, the humanitarian
crisis in Yemen, with approximately 18 million Yemenis facing (as of February 2026) acute hunger (The
International Rescue Committee, 2025) further highlights the failures of peacekeeping organisations and
policies such as ceasefires. The key challenges include setting up a neutral UN-monitored force that can
effectively enforce a ceasefire, reduce tensions at sea, and make sure that humanitarian aid reaches those
in need. Another major difficulty is managing the ongoing rivalry between Saudi Arabia and Iran while
addressing the Houthis’ demands for more political autonomy. Additionally, preventing terrorist groups
from gaining funding and support is complicated due to the country’s fragmented and weakened system of
governance.

As the Security Council engages with these issues of conflict head-on, it invites pioneers who are
prepared to move beyond mere rhetoric and look at new approaches - negotiate binding task forces,
reform international security and do all they can to safeguard a world which needs it more than ever.
Whether fueled by a commitment to dignity in action or a foresight which can change the future, the
security council promises fruitful debate and resolutions which will define a new era in international
security.

We look forward to welcoming you to the United Nations Security Council at SISMUN 2026!

Warm regards,
Siddhanth Chawla,
President of the United Nations Security Council,

Aarav Naik and Yidam Verma,
Deputy Presidents of the United Nations Security Council,
SISMUN 2026
