ECOSOC writeup

MEET THE EXECUTIVE BOARD

President of ECOSOC: Ayontika Naha
Deputy Presidents of ECOSOC: Nathan George and Anya Narayan

“Thousands have lived without love, not one without water.”
—W. H. Auden

Dear Delegates and MUN Directors,
The pursuit of sustainable development is no longer a distant dream in a world where access to food,
water, and humanitarian assistance remains challenging. As conflicts intensify, climate pressures mount,
and resource scarcity deepens, there is an immediate need for practical, comprehensive, and cooperative
solutions to protect vulnerable parts of society and promote long term economic-stability.
In ECOSOC, delegates will work on developing resolutions for two pressing challenges that strike the
very foundations of sustainable development: the urgency of food security in conflict zones and water
security through equitable water sharing of rivers in South Asia.
Our first agenda, "Emergency Measures to Enhance Food Security and Distribution of Humanitarian Aid
in Conflict Zones Across Sudan and South Sudan" tackles the severe humanitarian crisis unfolding in
Sudan and South Sudan. Ongoing violence, mass displacement and the collapse of essential services have
pushed millions towards acute food insecurity, with children facing alarming levels of malnutrition and
preventable disease. In several regions, blocked humanitarian access and attacks on health facilities have
disrupted life-saving assistance and deepened famine risks. This agenda urges ECOSOC to prioritise
coordinated emergency responses that secure humanitarian systems, restore food supply chains, protect
healthcare facilities, and ensure the safe and effective delivery of aid to the most vulnerable populations
amidst conflict.
Our second agenda, “Ensuring equitable water sharing of Trans-boundary River Systems of South Asia
for Environmental Protection and Water Security”, sets out to examine political tensions within South
Asian countries over freshwater resources. The Indus, the Ganges, and the Brahmaputra are the major
river systems that cross borders, flowing through India, Pakistan, and Bangladesh. This is referred to as a
transboundary. These rivers are significant contributors to water resources in all three countries, creating
interdependence and subsequently, conflict. Documents such as the Indus Water Treaties of 1960 and the
Ganges Water Treaty of 1996 have been criticised for being outdated, as they do not account for the
growing water demands of both countries due to population growth. Additionally, climate change poses a
significant threat to water security in South Asia, particularly for transboundary rivers such as the Indus,
Ganges, and Brahmaputra. This agenda appeals to ECOSOC to develop relevant frameworks for

water-sharing to resolve significant challenges in the face of growing water demands, climate change, and
environmental degradation.
As the world confronts conflict-driven hunger and intensifying competition over shared water resources,
delegates at ECOSOC will be expected to participate in intense discussion, diplomatic cooperation, and
meticulous planning throughout the sessions in order to generate innovative, accurate, and pragmatic
resolutions. We expect a thorough examination of the historical failures and how these crises may have
developed differently had different choices been made. Whether addressing food insecurity in conflict
zones or advancing equitable water-sharing frameworks in South Asia, ECOSOC offers a platform to
shape policies that directly impact the economic and social wellbeing of millions of lives.
We look forward to welcoming you to ECOSOC at SISMUN 2026!
Warm Regards,
Ayontika Naha,
President of the Economic and Social Council
Nathan George and Anya Narayan,
Deputy Presidents of the Economic and Social Council
SISMUN 2026

