HRC writeup

Meet the Executive Board:
President of HRC: Plaksha Sachanandani
Deputy Presidents of HRC: Diva Meharchandani and Joshua Jose

“You must never be fearful about what you are doing when it is right.”
-Rosa Parks
Dear Delegates and Mun Directors,
The Human Rights Council is an important place where countries work together to make
things better for people. We are very happy to be your chairs for this meeting. We are looking
forward to working with you on two problems that affect people's lives.
The Human Rights Council is where countries talk about problems and try to find solutions.
As delegates your job is not just to talk, but to listen to others find ground and write plans that
can really help people. The two issues we will talk about today are different. Both are very
important. One is about helping people who're in danger in the Middle East because of who
they are. The other is about helping to protect democracy and basic rights in Nepal.
Our first topic is about people who're different from others in the Middle East. We need to
think about how to help them when there is war and instability. These people are at risk of
being hurt and treated unfairly. They often cannot get the help they need.
When there is a war everything falls apart. There is no law and order and armed groups take
over. This is when people who are different are most vulnerable. In countries like Syria, Iraq
and Yemen these groups have attacked them with violence because of who they are. When
there is no law these people have no one to turn to. They also cannot get the help they need
because they are afraid or not allowed to get it. The United Nations has said that help must be
given to everyone without exception.
The Human Rights Council has to write plans that make sure everyone is treated equally and
has access to the services. This means making sure that people who hurt others are punished
and that help is given to everyone equally. This means encouraging governments to change
laws that're unfair and to make new laws that protect people. Importantly it means reminding
everyone that human rights belong to all people everywhere no matter what.
We need to make sure that the Human Rights Council does its job and helps people who need
it. We need to work to make a difference in the lives of people who are struggling. The

Human Rights Council is a tool and we must use it to help people who are in danger. We will
discuss these issues. Try to find solutions that work for everyone.
The second topic, "Human Rights Frameworks and the Smooth Transition Towards a Future
Elected Parliament in the Light of Civil Unrest and Democratic Backsliding in Nepal" is
about problems that Nepal is facing. Nepal is having a lot of trouble with its government and
democracy. It is very important to protect Human Rights like the freedom to say what you
think gather with people and join politics.
Nepal had a fight and got rid of its king to become a democratic country. It has been very
hard for Nepal. The government has changed times. People are getting very frustrated with
their leaders. When the government is weak and people do not trust them things can get
worse. Human Rights are often taken away first.
There are three freedoms that are very important in Nepal now. The freedom of speech means
people should be able to say what they think and criticize leaders without being afraid. A free
press helps keep the government in check. The freedom to gather means people can protest
peacefully when they do not agree with something. The freedom to join politics means
everyone should be able to take part whether by voting or running for office. This includes
women, minorities and people from areas.
The goal is to have an elected parliament that people can trust. This can only happen if
Human Rights are protected. Delegates need to work to create systems that protect Human
Rights. They need to help Nepal have fair elections. This means creating rules that defend the
rights of protesters, journalists and activists. It means helping Nepals institutions, like the
election commission and courts get stronger. It means encouraging the government and
opposition groups to talk to each other. It means asking countries to observe the elections to
make sure they are free and fair.
The two topics are challenging. The Middle East needs help to stop people from being treated
because of who they are. Nepal needs help to build its institutions. These two issues are
connected by one truth: Human Rights are important everywhere for everyone. Whether it is
protecting a person who is running away, from violence or a journalist who is asking
questions the work of this council is to make sure all people can live with dignity, safety and
freedom. Delegates the challenges are big.. You have a lot of potential. We look forward to
seeing the solutions you create together.

