HSC writeup

Historic Security Council
President of HSC: Advait Vaishnav
Deputy Presidents of HSC: Kavish Goenka and Rithvik Singh
“The farther backward you can look, the farther forward you are
likely to see.”
— Winston Churchill
Dear Delegates and MUN Directors,
History is often seen as a closed chapter in our lives, as a sequence
of outcomes which we cannot change. In the Historic Security
Council (HSC), we aim to reopen that book and rewrite the pages
of history.
Our aim for this committee is not just to look back at the events of
the past, but immerse ourself into crucial moments that have
defined the past and continue to influence today’s geopolitical
landscape. The choices made by the delegates of this committee
have the power to change the course of history in this alternate
universe where the ink on treaties hasn’t yet dried and every
decision carries the weight of an uncertain future. By changing the
outcomes of these defining moments, we directly advance the
SISMUN Conclave theme: Working Towards Fostering an
Ecosystem of a Uniform Global Human Rights and Social Justice
Framework. In this HSC, security decisions become human rights
imperatives, preventing mass suffering, upholding
self-determination, and building equitable global norms that echo
into our world today. Our advise for you is to move beyond the
luxury of hindsight. We ask you to inhabit the perspectives and
policies of a different era.
Our first agenda: “The implications of Cuban Missile Crisis and
the Deployment of Strategic
Weapons in the Caribbean” deals with the wake of the failed Bay
of Pigs invasion (1961) and the persistent threat of Operation
Mongoose, the geopolitical landscape of the Caribbean has shifted
from a regional dispute to the epicenter of a nuclear standoff.

Following the arrival of Soviet "agricultural technicians" and the
subsequent U-2 aerial confirmation of SS-4 medium-range ballistic
missiles near San Cristobal, the United States has enforced a naval
"quarantine" of the island. The Council must now navigate the
fallout of this brinkmanship. Beyond the immediate threat of
nuclear annihilation, we must address the violation of the Monroe
Doctrine, the legitimacy of the Soviet-Cuban alliance, and the
failure of traditional diplomacy to prevent the deployment of
strategic weapons in the Western Hemisphere.
Freeze Date: 24th October, 1962
Our second agenda: “The Proposed Formation of an Independent
Government in East Pakistan” explores the Pakistani unification’s
breaking point. Following the central government’s perceived
negligence during the 1970 Bhola Cyclone and the subsequent
refusal to honor the Awami League’s landslide victory in the
general elections, the social contract in the East has vanished. The
launch of Operation Searchlight on March 25, 1971, has
transformed a political deadlock into a humanitarian catastrophe.
With over 10 million refugees pouring into India and the Mukti
Bahini engaging in escalating guerrilla warfare, the stability of
South Asia hangs in the balance. The Council is tasked with
addressing the proposed formation of a future independent
government and the systemic human rights violations occurring in
the Ganges Delta. We must determine if a federal solution is still
viable or if the international community must facilitate the birth of
a new sovereign state amidst the ruins of a fractured union.
Freeze Date: 3rd December, 1971
Throughout the sessions, delegates will be expected to engage in
rigorous debate, diplomatic collaboration, and the meticulous
drafting of paperwork to produce resolutions that are creative,
precise, and practical. We urge you to scrutinize the shortcomings
of the past and explore how these crises might have unfolded if
alternate decisions had been made.
With the goal of achieving high-level dialogue and creative
problem-solving, I, alongside my Deputy Presidents, Kavish Goenka
and Rithvik Singh, am honored to welcome you to the Historic
Security Council at SISMUN 2026.

Sincerely,
Advait Vaishnav
President of the Historic Security Council,
Rithvik Singh and Kavish Goenka
Deputy Presidents of the Historic Security Council,
SISMUN 2026

