Disec writeup

President of DISEC: Satvik Agarwal

Deputy Presidents of DISEC: Medhansh Saha and Vivaan Varshney
“It has become appallingly obvious that our technology has exceeded our humanity.”

— Albert Einstein

Dear Delegates and MUN Directors,
From the ruins of a war that unleashed the most devastating weapons humanity had ever seen,
the United Nations was established in 1945. The First Committee of the General Assembly,
the Disarmament and International Security Committee, was given a single task: to make sure
that the weapons of war would never again surpass the conscience of their operators. That
purpose is more important now than it has ever been, eight decades later. These days,
algorithms are able to choose targets more quickly than a human can blink, and the politics of
resource and identity, in addition to armies, are redrawing the borders of sovereignty. At
DISEC, we do more than just argue; we take on the forces that will determine whether the
upcoming decades are characterized by collaboration or disaster.
This committee's two agenda items are situated at the nexus of geopolitical change and
technological progress. Before those weapons rule the battlefield, one wonders if mankind
can control the weapons it is creating. The other question is whether the international
community can accommodate a people's desire for self-determination without upsetting the
fragile framework of sovereignty that sustains the world order. Both need diligence,
imagination, and a readiness to tackle problems for which there are no simple solutions.
Delegates are thrown into one of the most important arms control discussions of the
twenty-first century with our first agenda item, "Regulating Lethal Autonomous Weapon
Systems (LAWS) and Military Applications of Artificial Intelligence to Maintain
International Peace and Security." These days, lethal autonomous weapon
systems—platforms that can choose and attack targets without significant human
involvement—are not just a thing of science fiction. The machinery of war is changing at a
rate that international humanitarian law was never intended to handle, from AI-driven
monitoring and targeting systems to autonomous drones stationed in combat areas. This
committee's main concern is whether or not a machine can ever make the choice to end a
human life, and if it can, under what circumstances? The suitability of current legal
frameworks, such as the Geneva Conventions' tenets of distinction, proportionality, and
accountability; the Convention on Certain Conventional Weapons' (CCW) function in
creating new protocols; and the geopolitical realities of an arms race in which major powers
are unwilling to give up strategic advantage are among the issues that delegates must debate.
To ensure that the rights and dignity of persons ensnared in the march of technology are not
violated, this committee must work to draft resolutions that strike a balance between
innovation and responsibility.

A question that concerns both the future of the Arctic and the unresolved legacy of colonial
relationships is presented to the committee in our second agenda item, "The Question of
Granting Greenland Conditional Autonomy from Denmark with Regards to Use of Their
Own Resources and a Step Towards Nationhood." Since 2009, Greenland, which is inhabited
by Inuit people and contains enormous deposits of uranium, oil, and rare earth minerals, has
been governed under a system of self-government under the Kingdom of Denmark. However,
in the face of climate change opening new shipping routes, growing interest from
international powers in Arctic resources, and a renewed assertion of indigenous
self-determination, the island's aspirations for greater sovereignty—particularly over the
extraction and revenue of its own natural resources—have intensified. The legal and political
aspects of conditional autonomy must be examined by delegates, including the economic
feasibility of an independent or semi-independent Greenland, the rights of indigenous peoples
under international law, the strategic ramifications for NATO and Arctic security, and the
precedent that any resolution may set for global self-determination movements. The
committee's job is to create a framework that is reasonable, practical, and principled while
respecting Denmark's sovereignty and the rightful ambitions of the Greenlandic people.
This year's DISEC agendas are not only theoretical endeavors. These are pressing issues that
have actual ramifications for millions of people. The stakes are real, and prompt, deliberate
action is required, whether it is for the Greenlandic community whose future depends on
decisions made in far-off capitals or the civilians in a combat zone who may one day be
subject to the judgment of an algorithm. We anticipate that delegates will arrive
well-researched, with a solid grasp of their nation's stance, and with the diplomatic ability to
forge agreement when it appears impossible.
Together, the Executive Board of DISEC is honored to welcome you to the Disarmament and
International Security Committee at SISMUN 2026, where we want to achieve rigorous
discussion, innovative problem-solving, and significant results.

Sincerely,
The Executive Board of DISEC
SISMUN 2026

