[25/03/26, 7:27:20 PM] ~Zo: ICC writeup

President of ICC: Kiros Kamaal

Deputy Presidents of ICC: Anushka Bahorey and Viransh Shetty
"We need the law more than ever. Not the law in abstract terms, not the law as a theory for
academicians, lawyers and judges. But we need to see justice in action. People need to see that
the law has an impact on their lives."
– Karim A. A. Khan KC, ICC Prosecutor

Dear Delegates and MUN Directors,
The International Criminal Court (ICC) is the organisation that aims to give rise to justice
globally, it possesses the ability to prosecute genocide, humanitarian crimes, war crimes and
aggression crimes. The ICC supports communities who have been sidelined by the other
authorities for too long, ICC works in areas where humanitarian crimes have unfortunately
become a part of day to day life. The ICC works on the basis that law applies equally to anyone
and everyone.
Our first agenda: "The question of the Judicial Rights, Privileges and Accountability for the
Prisoners of Conscience taken from the Rohingya Population in Myanmar," calls delegates to
confront one of the most long lasting crises. The Rohingya, a muslim minority in Myanmar have
been discriminated against since the beginning of time. Marginalisation has ranged from
citizenship laws to targetted campaigns and devestating acts of genocide. Since the detrimental
area sweeps in Rakhine State, over 700,000 Rohingya have been forcibly displaced into the
neighbouring country, Bangladesh (UNHCR, 2025), while those who manage to stay back are
subjected to extremist humanitarian crimes. In November 2024, ICC Prosecutor Karim Khan
requested arrest warrants for Myanmar’s military leadership (Human Rights Watch, 2024).

Within this context, "prisoners of conscience" from the Rohingya population raise vital
questions about the scope of the ICC’s responsibility. Although Myanmar is not a State Party to
the Rome Statute, the Court has asserted its authority over crimes that intertwine between
borders, for instance, the occurrences of deportations of Rohingya into Bangladesh. Bangladesh
is a member state and hence allows the ICC to exercise its authority while the crimes transcend
between borders. This is one of the reasons delegates of this committee will need to comprehend
complex legalities, for instance if local courts are complicit or incapacitated, how will the rights
of Rohingya be safeguarded? What privileges and protections, fair trial guarantees, protection
from refoulement and reprisals are given to prisoners of conscience under international human
rights? The key challenges involve navigating areas of jurisdiction and complementarity. The
balance between justice for victims and Myanmar’s non cooperation. Not just this but how
delays in intervention may reduce trust in international institutions.
Our second agenda: “Setting up a Truth and Reconciliation Tribunal for Accountability of
Crimes Against Humanity during the ongoing and still unfolding Venezuelan Political Crisis,”
puts delegates in the middle of criminal accountability, transitional justice and the use of
administrative measures to suppress opposing parties. Venezuela’s crisis is further polarised by
rigged elections, forcedl suppression to move towards being autocratic and politically motivated
humanitarian crimes (OHCHR, 2025). While the ICC acknowledges these conflicts, ICC has
continued their investigations into “Venezuela I”, is meant to emphasise the ICC’s authority
(Coalition for the ICC, 2024).
The development of a truth and reconciliation tribunal in this context has varied difficulties but
extreme significance. It is crucial for delegates to understand how this tribunal would relate to
the ICC’s current investigations. Key issues of the debate will include the scope of its official
orders and jurisdictions with important focus on human rights in a politically polarised
environment while simultaneously measuring the roles of local organisations in monitoring or
aiding the ICC’s work. Another vital aspect is to focus on the after effects of the actions the ICC
proceeds with, Will the societal mindset change? Will the Rohingya population truly be safe
afterward? How will monitoring and safekeeping take place without interference of local biases?
As the ICC at SISMUN dives into these agendas, it calls for delegates who are willing to think
beyond slogans and who let actions speak louder than words. The ones who can manage the hard
trade offs required when international justice has to be reincarnated. Deciding between peace and
justice, sovereignty and accountability, punishment and reconciliation. Whether a delegate's
motivation lies in a principled commitment to human dignity, a keen interest in laws and
regulations or a registering equity and equality by viewing conflicts through the eyes of victims
rather than global states: this committee relies on out of the box institutional design and ethical
debate. As Presidents of this committee we require you to not arrive with only deep research but

with open mindedness, interrogative skills, working with empathy and last but not least building
frameworks that speak to real communities that seek justice.

We look forward to welcoming you to the International Criminal Court at SISMUN 2026!

Warm regards,

Kiros Kamaal,
President of the International Criminal Court,
SISMUN 2026

Anushka Bahorey and Viransh Shetty,
Deputy Presidents of the International Criminal Court,
SISMUN 2026

