[25/03/26, 7:28:31 PM] ~Zo: UNEP writeup

United Nations Environment Programme
SISMUN 2026
President of the UNEP Committee: Krishiv Agarwal
Deputy Presidents of the UNEP Committee: Anushka Iyer & Yatharth Bhati
“The Earth is what we all have in common.”
— Wendell Berry
Dear Delegates and MUN Directors,
Worldwide ecosystem degradation is no longer merely an environmental concern,
and is now an imperative threat to human welfare, climate resilience, and economic
prosperity. The Bay of Bengal islands are lush with biodiversity and home to
vulnerable coastal communities. They also intersect some of the most pressing global
crises today, including climate change, ecosystem degradation, and sustainable
development goals. However, the region is under immense pressure to expand
existing development, risking permanent harm to marine ecosystems, mangroves,
and coral reefs.
The UNEP committee on “Addressing the Degradation of Ecosystems and
Strengthening Global Protection Frameworks” spearheads the agenda for this
initiative, seeking to establish international partnerships and efforts to protect these
ecosystems. This committee is pertinent because it aligns with the climate-related
efforts ongoing around the world and the need to safeguard developments with
protections in place for the environment.
Given UNEP’s focus on these initiatives, this committee works to create
ecosystem-based adaptation and comprehensive protection frameworks. For
instance, as UNEP’s Economics of Ecosystems and Biodiversity Initiative reported,
the limited funding to restore ecosystems such as that for mangrove forests that is
partially secured through development projects still offers a far better return for what
is invested with lower costs of coastline maintenance and a more plentiful supply of
resources for communities affected. Preserving these ecosystems will ensure that the
communities vulnerable to climate change will be safeguarded. The dangers posed by
climate change to these ecosystems, such as rising sea levels and catastrophic storms,

will only worsen with time. This committee will enable the integration of
developments alongside robust efforts to ensure the environmental protection of
these areas, leaving space for these ecosystems to flourish alongside economic
developments.
Our committee will set forth to debate our sole agenda, which focuses on ecosystem
degradation in the Bay of Bengal islands as a result of rapid mangrove and coral reef
loss due to urbanisation and industrial activity, polluting and threatening
biodiversity that is crucial for coastal protection. The Sundarbans are, globally
speaking, the largest mangrove forest, yet they face habitat shrinkage and salinity
intrusion. Obstacles include coordination across littoral states with differing
priorities in order to protect the environment. Insufficient data related to ecosystem
health may further hinder effective solutions, but the welfare of local communities
must remain at the forefront.
Strengthening global protection regimes is essential for sustainable development in
the Bay of Bengal. Existing international programs such as REDD+ and the Paris
Agreement provide significant precedent for climate action, but implementation is
plagued by enforcement gaps and lack of funding. Emerging global initiatives such as
the UN High Seas Treaty bring aspirational targets such as 30 percent ocean
protection by 2030, but implementation remains a challenge. States must balance
the protection of national jurisdictions with collective ecosystem management,
equitable access to resources, and technology transfer, while navigating competing
national ambitions for economic development. Delegates will encounter issues
around whether binding commitments should be prioritised over voluntary
compliance, the best ways to direct climate finance into ecosystem restoration, and
where to place Blue Economy ambitions within broader development priorities.
Promoting Ecosystem-Based Adaptation and resilience-building offers an alternative
that uses nature’s own systems, such as restoring mangroves, to protect coasts and
provide communities with climate-resilient fisheries and coastal resources, while still
permitting sustainable use. However, upscaling these successful programs will
require long-term financing, scientific monitoring, adaptive management, and
meaningful community participation rooted in equitable benefit-sharing. Delegates
will encounter dilemmas around whether to prioritise nature-based solutions over

engineered alternatives, how to blend traditional ecological knowledge with modern
science, and how to govern community adaptation in ways that empower
communities rather than simply fulfilling international requirements. These
dilemmas highlight the tension between inclusive climate-resilient development
pathways and approaches that prioritise environmental protection alone.

As we come together to tackle these overlapping challenges, your participation will
ensure we develop practical solutions that balance progress with environmental
integrity. There is no other forum like this committee for us to work together and be
creative in finding solutions that will improve the resilience of not just this region but
also our planet. Let us all embark on this journey together to safeguard the precious
ecosystems of the islands of the Bay of Bengal so that they can continue to provide
for all living beings and protect us from the impacts of climate change for many
generations.

Sincerely,
Krishiv Agarwal
President, UNEP
Anushka Iyer
Deputy President, UNEP
Yatharth Bhati
Deputy President, UNEP Committee